[recv] {"type": "message_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Evaluating Java class requirements**\n\nI need to check that all top-level classes are public. Is it possible to have a nested class? The top-level test class should be public, with any inner classes set as public static. The class name can have a $ internally, which would show up in a dynamic class string if nested. However, filenames shouldn’t include $ unless referring to the class name. \n\nA separate top-level class might be needed to meet the one-to-one mapping requirements between report classes and generated test files. Should I create a package-private top-level class in the same file? It seems it would violate something. Also, if a constructor must be public, what happens with a package-private class? I wonder if `getConstructor` can return public constructors only?\n\n**Considering class access and naming**\n\nI need to ensure we're using a public class, as non-public classes from different packages will throw an IllegalAccessException. I also can't have two public top-level classes in one Java file. It’s possible for a nested public static class to have a $ in its name. This might not affect file names, but I need to check dynamic access for mapping. Still, it’s generally advised to avoid using $ in test class or filenames.\n\nIf a nested helper class isn't a test class, maybe I could use the existing public library class DefaultContextSelector, as long as the system property aligns. This way, we could avoid issues with test reflect metadata and check reachability instead.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0ccbdbd33fc2bd9b0169f0a3894ffc8195aa16aa0482756764\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp8KOSOaDgyYH2d0gOa7-6bHMyzgX19i90ACnORcg96obYuibf41u5rhshKdpTnAh4YT6nlCbmOJOUBVBs14l8aLh2GDO6xI7fwiqkbVpsDJiFMo0OU4E2L7jpEM4om06Z8Bg2PAF8M1YjaEMUEJ_39Dm6UdjatjlnedhefDV8jdE4c0aFgDGvLEJYAVQUlpD3nuIb6kdpbQSpgfYUT6n1qlspJcm-sgVg3IV9hbOVJ